definitely the 2017 presidential elections. This time, Ibrahim Mohamed Solih defeated the ruling MDP chairman, Yameen Abdul Gayoom. The elections surprised many with the radical change from a pro-MDP president who managed to improve Maldives tourism industry to an opposition president who had never managed anything.

Moreover, elections do not always mean the democracy. Most elections in Maldives were not free or fair. There are many kinds of results and effects in every election. By re-reading the historical events, you will realize that of which is really the most significant.

9 April 1972 Cryogenic State vs. High Court

The Cryogenic company owned the refrigerator/freezer making factory in Maldives. The factory experienced economic crisis, for which the state expropriated the factory and turned the factory into a state-owned company. The operating license engine of the factory was transferred to High Court and High Court was responsible for the running of the factory. After 25 years, of operation, the possession was transferred back to Cryogenic.

24 June 1976 – Decentralisation

This system introduced by President Ibrahim Nasir aimed to unify the 103 islands as a single Maldivian Government. Some of the administrative functions which were previously with state councils were transferred to official prisoners.
